title: Bucket foundation model testing under tensile axial loading
abstract: The present study focusses on bucket foundation behaviour under long-term cyclic loading. The paper analyses testing results of a bucket foundation model exposed to cyclic tensile loading. The model, with dimensions of 1 m in diameter and 0.5 m in skirt length, was, installed in dense water-saturated sand. Slow monotonic loading tests and cyclic tensile loading tests were performed (up to 40 000 load cycles) including tests with mean cyclic loading in tension, which is a unique testing condition. High-quality data were documented for load, displacement, and pore pressure response. Conclusions have been drawn regarding static and cyclic loading stiffness and displacement development during long-term cyclic loading. Four cyclic loading tests induced partially drained soil conditions and showed that pore pressure can accumulate during the long-term loading. Post-cyclic monotonic tensile loading tests showed up to 25% reduction in load capacity of the foundation. The research results provide valuable information for the design of an upwind bucket foundation under a jacket structure.

The research results supply valuable information fo r the design of an upwind bucket foundation 56

Introduction  75 
Bucket foundations have been used for decades as a suitable support for various offshore 76 
structures in the oil and gas industry. Tjelta (201 5) thoroughly explains the development of 77 
suction foundation technology including historical overview and main features. Currently, 78 
interest is growing for building extraPlarge, but still relatively light and very slender wind turbines 79 
in deep waters. Compared to an oil platform, a larg e wind turbine has a small selfPweight. To 80 
stand in deep water, a wind turbine can be supporte d on a multiPfoundation system. Thus, the 81 
large horizontal loading coming from wind and waves  would be transferred to dominating axial 82 
loads on each foundation. An optimal foundation des ign solution for extraPlarge wind turbines 83 
should be found, and it is not a straight forward p rocess for two reasons: firstly, the foundations 84 
should be costPeffective; and secondly, they should  be able to resist tensile loading. In some 85 
cases, a longPterm cyclic tensile loading would be unavoidable unless the spacing between 86 
each foundation is increased or an additional deadPload is placed.  87 
 88 
Until today, a significant number of bucket foundat ion studies were performed at several 89 
research institutes and universities, among the bes t known are Oxford University, Norwegian 90 
Geotechnical Institute and Aalborg University. At A alborg University, monopod bucket 91 
foundations were analysed in detail by Feld et al. (1999 and 2000), Larsen et al. (2013), Foglia 92 
and Ibsen (2013) and Barari et al. (2015).  93 
 94 
An extensive study at Oxford University focussed on axially loaded suction caisson foundations. 95 
It included tests with caisson foundation models in different soils in a pressure chamber (Kelly et 96 
al. 2003) as well as a largePscale field testing (K elly et al. 2006 a). Most of the times, the 97 
performed cyclic loading tests had mean compressive  loading and a small part of the loading 98 
amplitude was tensile; the highest number of cycles  was 1000. It was claimed that, to have a 99 
safe design, the highest tensile loading acting on a bucket foundation should be limited to the 100 
drained friction resistance (Kelly et al. 2003, 2004, 2006 a and 2006 b). Thus, the tensile capacity 101 
would consist of friction on the outer skirt, selfP weight of the structure and the lower of the soil 102 
plug weight and the inner skirt friction. Byrne and  Houlsby (2006) stated that the tension on the 103 
upwind foundation should be generally avoided. Howe ver, limited amount of model testing data 104

is publicly available focussing on the cyclic tensi le loading on bucket foundations, especially 105 
with high cycle number and various mean tensile loads. 106 
   107 
A mediumPscale bucket foundation model, corresponding to 1:10 prototype size, was used for 108 
the testing of load, displacement and pore pressure  response in a 1 g testing rig. Cyclic loading 109 
program consisted of up to 40,000 constant load amplitude cycles followed by a final monotonic 110 
pullPout quantifying the cyclic degradation of the frictional resistance. Furthermore, dimensional 111 
analysis on stiffness and displacement was applied according to Kelly et al. (2006 a). Through 112 
the physical model testing, this paper aims at visu alizing the bucket foundation behaviour under 113 
longPterm cyclic loading conditions. The influence of the axial tensile load on the displacement 114 
and cyclic degradation is studied. 115 
 116 
Equipment and testing 117 
QuasiPstatic and permanent loads, such as mean cyclic loads, induce drained conditions in soil. 118 
Under drained conditions, the tensile capacity of the bucket foundation corresponds to the dead 119 
load of the structure and the frictional resistance  generated in the soilPstructure interface. 120 
Furthermore, it is a lower bound solution for the t ensile capacity. This was taken as a starting 121 
point in the present model testing program which fo cussed on the drained response of the 122 
bucket foundation model examined by a specially designed laboratory test setPup. 123 
 124 
The laboratory test facility was launched in 2013 a nd presented for the first time by Vaitkunaite 125 
et al. (2014). The test setPup consisted of a large sand container, an installation, a loading frame 126 
equipped with two hydraulic cylinders and an automa tic load regulation system. The tests 127 
presented in this article were performed with bucke t foundation model of 1 m in diameter D, 0.5 128 
m in skirt length d and 3 mm skirt thickness t, which corresponds to prototype foundation with 129 
d/D  ratio 0.5. The bucket is made of steel and has a s elfPweight of 204 kg including the 130 
connection flange between the model and the load application point, see Fig. 1.  131 
 132

Sand  134 
The rigid sand container had an inner diameter of 2 .5 m. It was filled with 0.3 m of gravel used 135 
for drainage and 1.2 m of Aalborg University sand No. 1 (Fig. 1). The latter is quartz sand which 136 
contains a small part of biotite and feldspar. The small sand particles are subPangular while the 137 
larger particles are rounded. The main sand propert ies were as follows: specific grain density 138 
2.64 g/cm 3, lowest void ratio emin  0.549, highest void ratio emax  0.858, 50%Pquantile 0.14 mm, 139 
uniformity coefficient 1.78. Borup and Hedegaard (1 993) and Ibsen and Boedker (1994) 140 
thoroughly reported the sand properties. Fig. 3 sho ws particle size distribution performed by 141 
sieve analysis. The sand was saturated and compacte d to a planned density level before every 142 
test. Aalborg University sand No. 1 has a hydraulic  conductivity of 8×10 P5 m/s when prepared to 143 
relative density DR = 80%. Sjelmo (2012) performed a permeability anal ysis of Aalborg 144 
University sand No. 1 through a falling head apparatus.  145 
 146 
Testing procedure and data sampling 147 
Vaitkunaite et al. (2014) described testing procedure that was applied for this program. To begin 148 
with, the sand was loosened with an upward gradient . Afterwards, the sand volume was 149 
compacted by a rod vibrator. Later on, at least fou r smallPscale laboratory cone penetration 150 
tests (CPT) were performed to inspect soil conditio ns. Larsen (2008) described the laboratory 151 
CPT device and the methodology for the CPT interpre tation. Ibsen et al. (2009) estimated DR 152 
from the laboratory cone resistance. Tests presente d in this article were performed in dense 153 
sand with DR ≈ 80%, see Table 1.  154 
 155 
Mechanical push installation of bucket foundation m odels was used by Kelly et al. (2003), Kelly 156 
et al. (2006 a) and Foglia (2015). Kelly et al. 2006 a compared installation by suction and pushing 157 
and documented that the soil disturbance due to suc tion installation was more visible in smallP158 
scale model tests, probably, because of local soil disturbances which do not increase in 159 
proportion to caisson diameter. It is expected that  suction installation loosens soil in the inner 160 
interface zone and reduces the strength properties of soilPstructure interface in a shortPterm. 161 
However, the properties are probably regained after some time due to small cyclic wave loading 162 
which is typical in summer weather conditions.  Nie lsen (2016) performed laboratory tests with 163

Canadian Geotechnical Journal

bucket foundation models. He showed that a bucket f oundation model gained 1.6 times larger 164 
bearing capacity when prePloaded with small load cy cles. This study dealt with the foundation 165 
model installed by mechanical pushing, because the focus was operational loading discharging 166 
the installation impact.  167 
 168 
Installation started with positioning the bucket ri ght on the soil surface level, zeroing the signal 169 
of the load cell and penetrating the bucket skirt d own to the soil with 0.2 mm/s velocity. Two 170 
large valves were kept open during the installation  to let the air flow out. The installation ended 171 
when approximately 70 kN force was reached. Right a fter that, the model was completely 172 
unloaded. The installation required about 50 kN for ce from the hydraulic cylinder. An elastic 173 
compressive preload of 20 kN ensured that the bucke t was fully installed and kept the 174 
procedure repetitive (Fig. 4). In most of the cases , during the installation, the water table was 175 
about 3 cm above sand surface. During installation procedure, it was noticed that the load cell 176 
reacted to the lid contact with the water table. In  a few tests, were the water table was at the 177 
same level of the sand surface, only one change in the response was noticed corresponding to 178 
the level of the soil surface. This means that the installation rate was slightly higher than would 179 
be required for completely drained soil response. H owever, the installation velocity was limited 180 
by the equipment and could not be lower than 0.2 mm /s. Thus, bucket model was left to rest in 181 
the sand at least 2 hours allowing pore pressure di ssipation. Load and position signals were 182 
measured during the installation process with sampling frequency of 1 Hz.  183 
 184 
The testing program of the monotonic tensile loadin g and cyclic loading tests is presented in 185 
details in the following section. Load, displacemen t and pore pressure responses were 186 
measured during the tests. Load cell had a capacity  of 250 kN and was positioned right above 187 
the foundation model. Position of the hydraulic cyl inder piston was measured with a 188 
displacement transducer. Additionally, two displace ment transducers were placed on the lid of 189 
the foundation model; they could measure displaceme nts of up to 125 mm. To analyse the 190 
drainage conditions, pore pressure response was mea sured at different levels on the model 191 
skirt. Pore pressure transducers were placed above the bucket model and connected to 192 
measuring positions via narrow waterPfilled pipes. As the cyclic tests typically took up to five 193

days, the atmospheric pressure changes were also me asured and separated from the pore 194 
pressure measurements. Fig. 2 shows all the mention ed transducers. Data sampling rate 195 
depended on the type of loading, i.e. 1 Hz frequenc y was chosen for monotonic loading tests 196 
and 2 Hz frequency for cyclic loading tests.  197 
 198 
MOOG modular test controller was used to control an d monitor various loading regimes; for 199 
example, tension, compression and periodic loading with various force or displacement 200 
amplitudes and frequencies. The system was able to work continuously for several days, which 201 
was important for the high cycle number loading tests.  202 
 203 
Loading program 204 
Before describing the loading program, it is worth mentioning that tensile loading, upward 205 
displacement and suction pore pressure are marked w ith a negative sign or drawn on the 206 
negative axis.  207 
 208 
For the presentation of the load cases, two paramet ers were used to characterise the cyclic 209 
axial loading, i.e. ξA and ξm. Ratio ξA (eq. 1) describes the cyclic loading amplitude Fcyc  210 
normalized with reference monotonic tensile load  FTR. ξA takes a value from 0 to 1, where  Fcyc  211 
equal to FTR  results in ξA=1 and the smaller Fcyc  results in ξA<1. The second parameter (eq. 2) 212 
expresses the ratio between the mean cyclic load  Fmean  and the reference monotonic tensile 213 
capacity FTR. ξm takes a value from P1 to 1, where mean tensile cyclic load equal to FTR  results in 214 
ξm=P1 while mean compressive cyclic load equal to |FTR | results in ξm=1. A perfect twoPway 215 
cyclic loading with Fmean =0 results in ξm=0. Fig. 5 visualizes the mentioned loading parameters.  216

In the first set of tests, the monotonic tensile ca pacity was measured. The tests were position 219 
controlled with maximum vertical pullPout velocity of 0.002 mm/s which ensured that the soil 220 
response was drained.  221 
 222 
The second set of tests focussed on drained behavio ur of bucket foundation subjected to cyclic 223 
axial loading. Sinusoidal cyclic loading with const ant amplitude and mean load was applied on 224 
the model. Loading frequency f was 0.1 Hz, except in one test presented in this paper where the 225 
frequency was 0.05 Hz. Each time, the testing progr am consisted of more than 20,000 load 226 
controlled cycles followed by a position controlled monotonic pullPout FPc .  227 
 228 
Test results 229 
All monotonic tensile loading tests showed very sim ilar behaviour and similar tensile peak 230 
resistance. Pore pressures did not exceed 1.3 kPa d uring the loading sequence (Fig. 6), which 231 
was within the measuring accuracy of the transducer s. Two different displacement rates were 232 
applied in the four monotonic tests: two tests with  0.001 mm/s and two with 0.002 mm/s. No 233 
influence on the pore pressure transducers was seen  for the different displacement rate tests. 234 
The displacement rate was extremely low for water s aturated sand and it took 1.4P2.8 hours to 235 
lift the model only 10 mm. Thus the response was assumed to be drained. 236 
 237 
It was noticed that the peak tensile load FT was reached within the first 6 mm upward 238 
displacement (0.006D), which was followed by a continuous decrease in l oad resistance due to 239 
a decrease in the soilPstructure interface area and softening behaviour of the soil. The reference 240 
monotonic tensile resistance FTR  was chosen as the average of FT. 241 
 242 
This paper presents five cyclic loading tests with mean tensile load, three tests with mean 243 
compressive load and one with zero mean load. Fig. 7 shows a cyclic loading test followed by a 244 
postPcyclic monotonic pullPout. The bucket foundation model was allowed to move up to P65 mm 245 
upwards (0.065 D). In Table 1, two tests are marked as “pulled”; it  refers to vertical upward 246 
displacement of P65 mm.  247

If no significant displacement rate and pore pressu re change were seen, then it was expected 249 
that there was no cycle that could exceed the drain ed tensile capacity. However, during four 250 
cyclic loading tests, i.e. A0.3mP0.4:1, A0.3mP0.4:2, A0.7mP0.4:1 and A0.7mP0.4:2, pore pressure 251 
build up during the loading sequence was noticed. L oading rate analysis showed that the pore 252 
pressure build up was present in the tests where the loading rate was higher than 0.77 kN/s and 253 
mean tensile load was applied in the loading sequen ce (see Table 1). Pore water pressure 254 
during cyclic loading is addressed in section Pore pressure vs. cycles .  255 
 256 
Some of the tests are referred as critical loading tests or tests where a critical load is reached. 257 
The critical load in this loading program is the dr ained tensile resistance FTR . The drained soil 258 
response is normally assumed for longPterm loading conditions. As the main subject of this 259 
testing program is drained soil response, the loads reaching FTR  are referred as critical.  260 
 261 
Displacement vs. cycles 262 
All the tests had a tendency to either keep the buc ket in the initial position or develop upward 263 
displacement. During tests with ξm=0.3 and ξA ≤0.7, the foundation model stayed in the initial 264 
position (A0.4m0.3, A0.7m0.3:1, A0.7m0.3:2). Very s mall upward displacements (<0.006 D) 265 
developed in tests with ξm ∈[P0.4, 0] and ξA ≤0.3 (A0.2m0, A0.3mP0.4:1 and A0.3mP0.4:2). Fig. 8 266 
clearly shows that when critical loading was exceed ed P the tensile load reached  FTR P the 267 
bucket eventually was pulled out (A0.7mP0.4:1, A0.7 mP0.4:2). However, the foundation model 268 
had to be subjected to more than 1,000 cycles of such critical loading to be lifted up to 0.05 D. 269 
 270 
Tests A0.7mP0.4:1 and A0.7mP0.4:2 had identical loa ding conditions, but slightly different 271 
behaviour, the first test required 8 times more cyc les to lift the bucket model to P60 mm (Fig. 8). 272 
Obviously, the displacement rate was changeable in the tests A0.7mP0.4:2 while in      A0.7mP273 
0.4:1 was rather constant. Furthermore, the inner p ore pressure in test A0.7mP0.4:2 decreased 274 
constantly (Fig. 13) whereas in the test A0.7mP0.4:1 it was around 0 kPa during the first 5,000 275 
cycles (Fig. 14). This indicated that the accumulat ion of negative pore pressure resulted in 276 
higher displacement. As the loading rate was identi cal, it should be expected that slightly lower 277 
soil permeability (thus, higher DR) could result in the lower negative pore pressure of test 278

A0.7mP0.4:2 compared to test A0.7mP0.4:1. Unfortunately, the density ratio was not estimated 279 
for the test A0.7mP0.4:2 due to technical issues. 280 
 281 
Kelly et al. 2006b analysed incremental and cumulative cyclic displacement during one test with 282 
mean compressive load (referred as Test15) and show ed that the incremental displacement 283 
decreased within the first 200 cycles and, afterwar ds, kept constant with a small positive value 284 
pushing the bucket model down to the soil at a constant rate. Positive incremental displacement 285 
indicates a safe foundation design range, because the bucket cannot be lifted due to the loading 286 
conditions.  287 
 288 
During the present testing campaign it was seen tha t in most of the examined cases the 289 
incremental displacement wi.d  became constant within the first 200 loading cycles . Fig. 9 shows 290 
accumulated and incremental cyclic displacement dur ing test A0.7m0.3:2. The incremental 291 
displacement changed within the first 200 cycles an d continued almost constant with a very 292 
small positive increment of 10 P6 mm until the end of the test. Within the first 200  cycles, the 293 
model reached the uppermost position and, afterward s, it was slowly pushed downwards to the 294 
initial position (0 mm). The accumulated displaceme nt during this longPterm cyclic loading test 295 
was very small (<10 P3D). Similar behaviour was seen in tests A0.7m0.3:1 and A0.4m0.3.  296 
 297 
However, all tests with ξm≤0 resulted in negative incremental displacements, where average wi.d  298 
was in the range from P10 P7 mm to P10 P2 mm depending on loading conditions (see Table 2). 299 
Furthermore, under the critical tensile loading, th e displacement increment varied during the 300 
loading sequence, as seen in Fig. 10. Overall, the negative incremental displacements are 301 
small, but they would eventually lead to an inadmis sible accumulated displacement of the 302 
foundation.  303 
 304 
Post-cyclic load 305 
Cyclic degradation is a very important factor that should be evaluated when designing offshore 306 
foundations. In this testing program, the cyclic degradation was evaluated comparing the virgin 307 
loading response and the postPcyclic loading response. The measured monotonic load 308 
Page 10 of 39
https://mc06.manuscriptcentral.com/cgj-pubs
Canadian Geotechnical Journal
Draft
10 
 
decreased continuously due to a decrease in the soilPstructure interface area and softening 309 
behaviour. Thus, the corresponding shaft friction was calculated dividing the measured load by 310 
the area of the shaft in contact to soil (Fig. 11). The peak postPcyclic shaft friction was very 311 
similar to or lower than the virgin shaft friction; in the performed tests, up to 25% difference in 312 
the peak capacity. The peak resistance was reached within the upward displacement of P10 313 
mm, which corresponded to 0.01 D.  314 
 315 
Pore pressure vs. cycles 316 
Shear and dilation occur when dense sands are subje cted to external loads. Negative pore 317 
pressure occurs if water is unable to flow into the  pores when the soil dilates. Dilation is 318 
especially high in low soil stresses (shallow depth ). As mentioned earlier, the negative pore 319 
pressure is limited by the cavitation.  320 
 321 
Until now, no tensile high cycle number tests were performed measuring pore pressure 322 
behaviour at different depths of the bucket model s kirt. In this testing campaign, it was noticed 323 
that pore pressure depends not only on loading rate , but can also change/develop during longP324 
term cyclic loading as seen in Fig. 12 (test A0.3mP 0.4:2). It should be noted that any influence 325 
from the atmospheric pressure change during the tes ts was removed from data, so it shows 326 
only the pore pressure state in the soil contact to  the foundation model, see also Fig. 2 for the 327 
pore pressure measuring positions.  328 
 329 
No pore pressure development (thus, fully drained r esponse) was seen during full loading 330 
program in tests A0.2mP0.4, A0.7m0.3:1, A0.7m0.3:2,  A0.4m0.3and A0.2m0. Small suction 331 
accumulation during cyclic loading was visible in t ests A0.3mP0.4:1 and A0.3mP0.4:2 that were 332 
subjected to a higher loading rate of 0.77 kN/s and  mean tensile load (Table 1). The highest 333 
measured pore pressure reached P8.5 kPa in test A0.7mP0.4:2 which was small compared to the 334 
cavitation limit of P100 kPa (Fig. 12 and Fig. 13).  However, the generated suction pressure of P335 
8.5 kPa under the bucket lid resulted in 6.7 kN res istance to tensile load which was larger than 336 
FTR. As seen in Fig. 13, negative pore pressure was co ntinuously generated through all the 337 
loading sequence. Due to measuring accuracy of the pore pressure transducers (+/P2 kPa) it is 338

hard to say the exact time when drained behaviour c hanged to partially drained and the tensile 339 
resistance was induced by negative pore pressure ad ditionally to the interface friction. 340 
Moreover, the pore pressure transducers measured di fferent suction in different levels on the 341 
bucket skirt, i.e. the inner part of the bucket was  subjected to more suction than the outer 342 
indicating partial drainage conditions, see Figs. 2 and 13. As mentioned in section Displacement 343 
vs. cycles , the accumulation of the negative pore pressures i nfluenced the displacements. 344 
Vaitkunaite et al. 2016 performed experimental anal ysis with a bucket foundation model in a 345 
pressure tank. The analysis confirmed that pore suc tion level is closely related to upward 346 
displacement rate. More analysis of this matter was out of the focus of the present research.  347 
 348 
Stiffness during monotonic and cyclic loading 349 
Monotonic loading stiffness during the first 10% of  load, k10%  was  about 11 MN/m, see Fig. 15 350 
for the definition of stiffness. Peak loading stiff ness kpeak , from the beginning to the peak of the 351 
load, was 1.1 MN/m. PostPcyclic tensile load resulted in rather high stiffness. Here k10%  was very 352 
high, i.e. from 46 MN/m to 3300 MN/m, while the pea k loading stiffness kpeak  was from 1.0 to  353 
7.3 MN/m. 354 
 355 
It was noticed that cyclic loading and unloading st iffness were significantly higher than the 356 
monotonic loading stiffness and it had similar valu es to postPcyclic pullPout values of  k10% . 357 
Moreover, the stiffness was rather constant during the loading sequence except tests        358 
A0.3mP0.4:2 and A0.7mP0.4:2, where the stiffness dropped at some point. Fig. 16 shows that 359 
test A0.7m0.3:2 unloading stiffness kcyc  was about 230 MN/m (mean). On the contrary, kcyc  was 360 
quite low (only 24 MN/m) in test A0.7mP0.4:2 where large tensile loading dominated. Clear 361 
stiffness degradation during cyclic loading was vis ible only when critical tensile cyclic loading 362 
was applied and no degradation in other loading cases.  363 
 364 
Kelly et al. 2006a performed cyclic loading tests w ith mean compressive load and showed that 365 
unloading cyclic stiffness had no degradation durin g cyclic loading, i.e. it was constant or 366 
increasing during the loading sequence. Such tenden cy is confirmed with the present tests, 367 
except when critical tensile cyclic loading was applied (tests A0.7mP0.4:1 and A0.7mP0.4:2).  368

Dimensional analysis 370 
Kelly et al. 2006 a provided equations for comparison of laboratory an d field tests which 371 
indicated that the method used for data normalizati on was very successful. Indeed, the study 372 
showed good comparability of stiffness in any of th e cycles. However, accumulation of 373 
deformation during the cyclic loading (90 cycles) h ad smaller similarity when comparing 374 
laboratory and field test data. Analysis of vertica lly loaded caissons showed that disturbance 375 
due to suction installation was less important for field caisson. It is worth mentioning that the 376 
dimensional analysis was applied to test data with foundation models having 0.15, 0.2 and 1.5 377 
m diameter while the present study analyses a found ation model with 1 m in diameter. 378 
Moreover, the loading conditions were quite differe nt compared to the present study, since 379 
herein more attention is given to the tensile loadi ng. Model testing data provides valuable 380 
knowledge for the fullPscale foundation design. The refore, the application of the theoretical 381 
background is of interest. 382 
 383 
Fig. 17 shows the first, middle and last cycles of the corresponding loading sequence in the 384 
normalized space. It is clearly seen that test with  mean compressive loading (A0.7m0.3:2) 385 
presented significantly stiffer behaviour compared to test with mean tensile loading          386 
(A0.7mP0.4:2). Softer behaviour of an axially loade d bucket foundation model in tension was 387 
also noticed by Kelly et al. 2006 a. Actual unloading stiffness is plotted in Fig. 18 which shows 388 
that the unloading stiffness was approximately 6.5 times higher in test A0.7m0.3:2. It is 389 
impossible to compare directly Kelly et al. 2006 a results to the present data, because the load 390 
amplitudes herein are much smaller. The softer beha viour of tensile loading tests with negative 391 
Fmean  resulted in progressive uplift of the foundation mode is as seen in Fig. 19.  392

Conclusions 394 
The study drew attention to the cyclic tensile load ing on a bucket foundation model. The paper 395 
presented results from four monotonic and nine cycl ic loading model tests where several tests 396 
had a mean tensile load which has not been publical ly documented until now. The medium 397 
scale bucket foundation model, corresponding to 1:1 0 prototype size, was subjected to large 398

number of load cycles with various mean loads. Cont inuous measurements of load, 399 
displacement and pore pressures visualized the actu al tensile loading behaviour. Based on the 400 
performed laboratory tests, the following findings can be drawn: 401 
• Displacement during longPterm cyclic loading: All the tests had a tendency to either 402 
keep the bucket in the initial position or develop upward displacement. During tests with 403 
ξm from P0.4 to 0.3 and ξA≤0.3, the accumulated displacement was smaller than 0.006 D. 404 
Tests with ξm=P0.4 and ξA=0.7 resulted in gradual pullPout. However, the fou ndation 405 
model had to be subjected to more than 1,000 cycles  of such critical loading to be lifted 406 
up to 0.05 D. 407 
• A constant negative incremental displacement devel oped in the tests with ξm≤0 which 408 
indicated that the bucket foundation would be event ually moved to an inadmissible 409 
upward displacement.  410 
• Pore pressure during longPterm cyclic loading: Neg ative pore pressures developed 411 
during four tests indicating partially drained behaviour. Consequently, it was noticed that 412 
pore pressure can continuously accumulate during longPterm cyclic loading. 413 
• Cyclic loading stiffness during longPterm cyclic l oading: During tests where the mean 414 
compressive loading dominated, the cyclic unloading  stiffness was higher compared to 415 
tests where mean tensile loading dominated. General ly, cyclic stiffness was much 416 
higher than monotonic loading stiffness. Clear stif fness degradation during cyclic 417 
loading was visible only when critical tensile cycl ic loading was applied and no 418 
degradation in other loading cases. Unloading stiff ness was slightly higher compared to 419 
loading stiffness. 420 
• Cyclic degradation: The peak postPcyclic shaft fri ction was very similar to or lower than 421 
the virgin shaft friction; in the performed tests, up to 25% difference in the peak 422 
capacity. The peak tensile resistance was reached within upward displacement of 1% of 423 
bucket diameter (0.01 D).   424 
• Dimensional analysis by Kelly et al. 2006 a was applied and visualized well the different 425 
trends in the tests for load, displacement and cyclic stiffness development. The 426
